        h2#hed.
            From Hack <br/>
            to Hacker

        h3#deck An ongoing journey

        hr#rule

        p.
          Less than three months ago, as of this writing, I knew only enough HTML and CSS
          to break a website. I've come a long way since. Now I can break multiple sites
          at once.

        p.
          Not quite a year out from being laid off from a job in the thriving world of
          print journalism, I've taken a detour back to another interest of mine—technology.
          I've set out on a mission to learn to code, to create clean, logical websites and apps,
          and to learn the correct way to accomplish these tasks. Halfway through the Nashville Software
          School program, I'm well on my way to that goal but with the knowledge that
          I'll never be done learning.

        p.
          Here are many of the concepts, applications and frameworks that I've been exposed
          to so far in two and a half months:

        .row#list
          .col-md-4
            ul.list
              li HTML
              li CSS
              li JavaScript
              li AJAX
              li jQuery
              li Underscore

          .col-md-4
            ul.list
              li Lo-Dash
              li LESS
              li JADE
              li Foundation
              li Bootstrap
              li Vim

          .col-md-4
            ul.list
              li Command line usage
              li Sublime Text
              li Atom
              li Git and GitHub
              li TDD testing
              li Pair programming

        p.
          Some of these I know pretty well, of others I have just a passing knowledge. Sometimes
          I feel like a kid surrounded by shiny things, wanting to reach out and explore them all
          at once.

        p.
          The links in the carousel above take you to a few of the programs I've made as part of the
          learning experience. Both the Shell and Memory games demonstrate the use of JavaScript and
          jQuery to dynamically manipulate DOM elements. Quiz-O-Matic adds data sets to the equation.
          And Fireside Chat is my capstone project for the client-side portion of the NSS bootcamp.
          It utilizes an API call to read and write data to a Firebase database using only client-side Javascript.
          Yeah, they're still rough in places, and if you try hard enough you might break them.
          But what they represent is my ability to learn these concepts and turn
          that into practice. I look to update this site as I learn and accomplish more.

        p.
          And now I look forward to the second half of the NSS bootcamp involving server-side programming,
          so that I'll soon be able to work a full stack.

        p — James Nix


